# Gastrointestinal Endoscopy Image Classification
### BTech Minor Project — Computer Vision

---

## Project Summary

This project builds an automated image classification system for gastrointestinal (GI) endoscopy images using deep learning. The model classifies endoscopy images into 4 clinical categories using the HyperKvasir dataset and a ResNet18 neural network trained with PyTorch.

| Metric                | Score      |
|-----------------------|------------|
| Macro F1-Score        | 0.8969     |
| Balanced Accuracy     | 0.8999     |
| **Competition Score** | **0.8984** |
| Overall Accuracy      | 94%        |

---

## Dataset — HyperKvasir

- **Source:** https://datasets.simula.no/hyper-kvasir/
- **Download:** `hyper-kvasir-labeled-images.zip` (~4 GB)
- **Total images:** 10,662
- **Classes used:** 4 (normal, polyp, ulcer, inflammation)

| Class        | Images | Description                                        |
|--------------|--------|----------------------------------------------------|
| normal       | 6,035  | Healthy GI tract tissue                            |
| polyp        | 3,019  | Abnormal tissue growths, potentially pre-cancerous |
| inflammation | 851    | Ulcerative colitis, IBD                            |
| ulcer        | 757    | Esophagitis, Barrett's esophagus                   |

> **Note:** HyperKvasir has 23 original classes which are mapped to the 4 project classes above. Classes like `tumor`, `erosion`, `stricture` etc. are not present in HyperKvasir and are excluded.

---

## Project Structure

```
BTECH_PROJECT_ON_CV_ENDOSCOPY/
├── configs/
│   └── baseline_config.yaml     # Training configuration
├── data/                        # Prepared dataset (generated)
│   ├── images/
│   │   ├── normal/
│   │   ├── polyp/
│   │   ├── ulcer/
│   │   └── inflammation/
│   ├── metadata.csv
│   └── splits/
│       ├── train.csv            # 70% of data
│       ├── val.csv              # 15% of data
│       └── test.csv             # 15% of data
├── labeled-images/              # Raw HyperKvasir dataset
├── models/
│   └── best_model.pth           # Saved trained model
├── download_data.py             # Prepares HyperKvasir into project format
├── create_splits.py             # Creates train/val/test splits
├── train_model.py               # Model training script
├── generate_predictions.py      # Run inference on test set
├── evaluate.py                  # Evaluate predictions and print metrics
└── validate_submission.py       # Validate prediction file format
```

---

## Requirements

### System Requirements
- Python 3.11 (PyTorch does NOT support Python 3.12+)
- NVIDIA GPU recommended (tested on RTX 3070)
- ~10 GB disk space for dataset + model

### Install Dependencies

```bash
# Install PyTorch with CUDA (GPU support — RTX 3070 / CUDA 11.8)
py -3.11 -m pip install torch torchvision torchaudio --index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cu118

# Install remaining dependencies
py -3.11 -m pip install scikit-learn pandas numpy pillow tqdm pyyaml requests
```

> If you are on CPU only, remove the `--index-url` flag and install standard torch. Training will be significantly slower.

---

## How to Run — Step by Step

### Step 1: Download the Dataset

1. Go to: https://datasets.simula.no/hyper-kvasir/
2. Download `hyper-kvasir-labeled-images.zip` (~4 GB)
3. Extract it — you will get a folder called `labeled-images/`
4. Move `labeled-images/` into your project root folder

### Step 2: Prepare the Dataset

```bash
py -3.11 download_data.py --kvasir_dir ./labeled-images --output_dir ./data
```

What this does:
- Walks all 23 class folders inside HyperKvasir
- Maps them to the 4 project classes (normal, polyp, ulcer, inflammation)
- Copies images into `./data/images/<class>/`
- Generates `./data/metadata.csv` with image paths and labels

Expected output:
```
Found 10662 images
Dataset ready at: ./data
Class distribution:
  inflammation     851
  normal          6035
  polyp           3019
  ulcer            757
```

### Step 3: Create Train / Val / Test Splits

```bash
py -3.11 create_splits.py --data_dir ./data
```

- Splits data into 70% train, 15% validation, 15% test
- Uses stratified splitting to preserve class ratios in each split
- Saves `train.csv`, `val.csv`, `test.csv` into `./data/splits/`

Expected output:
```
Train: 7463 samples
Val:   1599 samples
Test:  1600 samples
```

### Step 4: Train the Model

```bash
py -3.11 train_model.py --config configs/baseline_config.yaml
```

What happens during training:
- Loads ResNet18 pretrained on ImageNet
- Replaces final layer with 4-class classifier
- Uses **Focal Loss** to handle class imbalance (normal has 6035 images vs ulcer with 757)
- Uses **WeightedRandomSampler** to give equal representation to all classes in each batch
- Saves best model to `./models/best_model.pth` based on competition score
- Training runs for 30 epochs (~15-20 minutes on RTX 3070)

Config file (`configs/baseline_config.yaml`):
```yaml
data_dir: "./data"
image_size: 224
batch_size: 32
learning_rate: 0.0005
num_epochs: 30
model_architecture: "resnet18"
pretrained: true
num_workers: 0
```

### Step 5: Generate Predictions

```bash
py -3.11 generate_predictions.py \
    --model_path ./models/best_model.pth \
    --test_csv ./data/splits/test.csv \
    --data_root ./data \
    --output predictions.json
```

- Loads the best saved model
- Runs inference on all 1600 test images
- Uses **Test-Time Augmentation (TTA)** — averages predictions across 5 augmented versions of each image for improved accuracy
- Saves results to `predictions.json`

### Step 6: Validate Submission Format

```bash
py -3.11 validate_submission.py --submission predictions.json
```

Checks that the prediction file is correctly formatted before evaluation.

Expected output:
```
VALIDATION PASSED
Total predictions: 1600
Unique images: 1600
```

### Step 7: Evaluate Results

```bash
py -3.11 evaluate.py --test_csv ./data/splits/test.csv --predictions predictions.json
```

Prints full evaluation including per-class metrics and confusion matrix.

---

## Model Architecture

| Component | Choice | Reason |
|-----------|--------|--------|
| Base model | ResNet18 | Lightweight, fast, strong baseline for medical imaging |
| Pretrained weights | ImageNet | Transfer learning — works well even for medical images |
| Final layer | Linear(512 → 4) | Replaced to match our 4 classes |
| Loss function | Focal Loss (γ=2) | Handles class imbalance better than CrossEntropy |
| Optimizer | AdamW (lr=0.0005) | Stable convergence with weight decay |
| LR Scheduler | Cosine Annealing | Gradually reduces LR for better fine-tuning |
| Sampler | WeightedRandomSampler | Balances class distribution in each training batch |

### Data Augmentation (Training)
- Random crop after resize
- Random horizontal and vertical flip
- Random rotation (±15°)
- Color jitter (brightness, contrast, saturation)
- ImageNet normalization

### Test-Time Augmentation (Inference)
Predictions are averaged over 5 versions of each image:
1. Original
2. Horizontal flip
3. Vertical flip
4. Center crop
5. 90° rotation

---

## Results — Per Class

| Class       | Precision | Recall | F1-Score | Support |
|-------------|-----------|--------|----------|---------|
| normal      | 0.96      | 0.94   | 0.95     | 906     |
| polyp       | 0.95      | 1.00   | 0.97     | 453     |
| ulcer       | 0.74      | 0.81   | 0.77     | 113     |
| inflammation| 0.94      | 0.85   | 0.89     | 128     |

The weakest class is `ulcer` (F1: 0.77) — this is expected as it has the fewest training images (757) and is visually similar to `inflammation`.

---

## Troubleshooting

| Problem | Fix |
|---------|-----|
| `ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'torch'` | Run with `py -3.11` instead of `python` |
| `Using device: cpu` despite having GPU | Reinstall PyTorch with CUDA: `py -3.11 -m pip install torch --index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cu118` |
| Out of memory during training | Set `batch_size: 16` in config |
| `BrokenPipeError` on Windows | Set `num_workers: 0` in config (already default) |
| PyTorch install fails | Make sure you are using Python 3.11, not 3.12+ |

---

## Future Improvements

- **Better model:** Switch to EfficientNet-B3 or ConvNeXt for higher accuracy
- **More data:** Source additional images for underrepresented classes
- **Ensemble:** Combine predictions from multiple models
- **Grad-CAM:** Add visual explainability to show which regions the model focuses on
- **Web demo:** Deploy as a Flask/Streamlit app for live image upload and prediction



